ies the evolution of markets and various market failures in these economies in particular her main areas of focus are agriculture and formal and informal financial access for example she has worked on the adoption of seed technologies in kenya and the extent of informal risk pooling mechanisms in rural kenya her ongoing research includes understanding the adoption and impact of mobile money m pesa in kenya the role of infrastructure in agricultural markets in sierra leone the diffusion of improved coffee farming practices through social networks in rwanda the role of different types of formal and informal collateral in credit markets for assets in kenya she regularly spends time in the field managing her various research projects and data collection activities tavneet is a faculty research fellow at the nber an affiliate of bread j pal and cepr and co director of agriculture research program at the international growth center location sloan mathematics center 450 serra mall bldg 380 room 380y stanford university stanford ca 94305 directions map fsi contact kathleen barcos parent research projects liberation technology seminar series program on liberation technology series topics economics liberation technology kenya rwanda sierra leone sub saharan africa search cddrl search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages events of interest liberation technology introduction to series vivek srinivasan liberation technology in authoritarian regimes conference pdf+ word doc+ the role of ushahidi as a liberation technology patrick meier audio+ designing technology to combat corruption vivek srinivasan video+ support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 4610 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
